description.text:
This is an upgrade for a printrbot simple to be able to use e3d hotend. I am using the e3d litev6. The motor sits nicely on the top of the rods and the e3d hotend is mounted on the bottom of the extruder board so there isn't any need to modify the old printrbot fan that you use to cool down the PLA.

UPDATE - now you can add auto-leveling probe

I have printed everything with 25% infill and it is holding fine.
You don't have to modify the printer at all. Just the firmware as it is in the manual of e3d.
The extruder bowden nicely holds in the printrbot metal extruder so no need to print any other extruder parts.

Feel free to leave feedback

Now you can add auto-leveling probe - need to modify the firmware for that

title: Improved Ultimate Power Supply Terminal Cover

description.text: Improved version of mike_linus's Ultimate Power Supply Terminal Cover. Designed to cover exposed screw terminals on power supplies commonly used with 3d printers and provide a switch and plug options.

This is an improved version of mike_linus's power supply terminal cover. The three main improvements were to add an option for round toggle switches, making the slot retainers cylindrical so they can be printed more easily, and making the retaining slots move up as you change the depth of the part. I also added comments for the MakerBot customizer and a lip to the bottom edge if you decide to make the cover deeper. Other improvements have been made to the OpenSCAD file which can be seen with the customizer tool. Each setting is commented and the parameters can be modified without breaking the file (i.e. if you change the size of the power input cutout it will be centered between the retaining screw holes). There was also a minor bug in the original part which caused the part to be slightly wider (2mm) than the configuration was set to. The default customizer settings will give you a slightly deeper version of the original Ultimate Power Supply Terminal Cover settings with a square switch. CUSTOMIZATION:
To use a round switch simply change the switch cutout length and width to zero and set the switch cutout radius sized to your switch. All other settings should work as expected. DISCLAIMER:
Please ensure you are careful with all wiring as any power supply modifications involve dangerous voltages. Do not perform these modifications unless you know what you are doing. Proceed at your own risk. I do not accept any liability.

description.text:
Bonjour,

J'ai modélisé un nouveau corps d'extrusion pour la Micro Delta.

Il est polyvalent et permet d'adapter plusieurs Hotends. Il est en deux parties afin d'interchanger facilement et rapidement les Hotends.

Les parties Inférieure et Supérieure sont assemblées avec deux boulons M4 de 45mm, tête fraisée et deux écrous papillons.

J'ai posté trois parties supérieures pour le moment. Une qui permet de fixer l'Héxagon hotend (d'origine sur la micro delta) et deux autres qui permettent de fixer le Hotend "All in one" de chez Fourmix mais en intégrant directement le Pneufit.
(Pneufit avec filetage M6 et Pneufit avec filetage 1/8")

La partie inférieure est fixée à l'imprimante.

Le Hotend et les ventilateurs s'adaptent à la partie supérieure de la même manière que sur le corps d'extrusion dorigine.

(J'ai remarqué une légère différence entre les cotes du modèle 3D et celles de la pièce imprimée avec ma micro delta, j'en ai donc tenu compte pour modéliser mon corps d'extrusion. N'hésitez pas à modifier vos pièces pour que tout s'adapte parfaitement. En cas de problème, n'hésitez pas à me contacter)

title: FolgerTech Prusa i3 Filament Spool Mount 6mm frame

description.text:
Just another spool mount for the prusa i3. After printing and using a few readily available mounts and not being satisfied with any of them, i decided to make my own. I wanted a mount that didn't require drilling into the frame, but was still very stable. Also being used on a plexiglas frame, i didn't want to stress the frame by having the spool hanging off the back. This is the design i came up with. Tall enough to be used without the spool holders. Spool holders do offer more clearance and better movement though. This design is for 6mm frames, but i can modify it for other thicknesses if there is any interest.

UPDATE 9/10/15 : Taking one nut off to remove / change the spool was a semi tedious process, so i made some quick collars that are held in place with a 3mm set screw. They also press strictly on the inner bearing race for smoother operation than with the nut. Use the nuts or the collar. Your choice.

If you make and use this design, please post your make / pic! Would love to see it!

I printed the spool mount at .3mm layer height with 2 perimeters and 3 top and bottom layers. 20% honeycomb infill.
Reel holder was printed at the same but 30% honeycomb infill.

UPDATE 9/10/15 : if using spool collars you'll need 2 M3 bolts

BOM: (IF USING REEL HOLDERS)
Length of M8 threaded rod (cut to whatever length you want mount spaced to)
2x M8 nuts or 2x M3x8 bolts (if using spool collars)
2x 608 bearings
2x M3x5/20 screws
2x M3 nuts

(IF NOT USING REEL HOLDERS aka minimal build)
2x M3x5/20 screws
2x M3 nuts
Length of M8 threaded rod or 8mm dowel ect

title: Swiss Army style keyring V2 with thumbnail cutouts

description.text:
I love the Swiss Army Keyring by outcastrc, but using it is a little cumbersome. It needed those little cut outs in the side that allow you to get a thumbnail in to grip the key to make opening it that much easier.  
So that's what this is.  The Swiss Army style keyring with cut outs.  
I have also moved the key ring clip as that was getting in the way of one of the keys.  
This version is intended to be used with M3 nuts and bolts.  
I've recreated the whole thing in openScad and the newest version is (mostly) parametric.   
Update: I had messed up the dimensions after using the minkowski sum function to add the curved edges on this model. I have reworked the scad file to take that into account and the dimensions are now back to the same as the original. Also the new scad file is much more parametric. I haven't tested how tollerant it is when changing dimensions, you may have to alter a few offsets here and there. If you do change it, let me know how you get on.  
I should also say that the one scad file now generates both sides. Just change the value of variable 'renderNutHoles' to either 1 or 0.  
You will also need to include functions.scad file in the same directory as the main scad file to render the cutouts for the nuts.

Print both sides, fit M3 nuts or M3 lock nuts to the side with the hex recess. Fit three M3 screws to the other side, adding M3 washers between the sides and keys. Nip the screws up and if needed cut the screws down to length (measure, remove, cut and refit).

title: Cup Holder for Citroen C5 III

description.text:
Let's be honest, the Citroen C5 (Mark III, built since 2008) is a nice and comfortable car perfectly made for long journeys. But during long jurneys I get thursty. So what the hell did they think when they made a single cup holder for the front row and put it under the arm rest?!? I've seen it and decided to never use it.
So where can I put my coffee-to-go or my can of lemonade once it is opened?
My research brought me to the following conclusions:

  1. There is no cup holder designed specifically for the C5.
  2. All the aftermarket standard cup holders either make that almost premium interior (your personal opinion may differ) look like a 1980s economy car, block the air ducts, cost way too much money, require drilling holes into the dashboard or even combine more of these characteristics.

So I couldn't buy any cup holder, GREAT! Another perfect justification I could give my wife for purchasing that "are you nuts this is way too expensive" 3D printer!
Said - done. 2-3 tries for improving printability, stability and usability and there it is:

  • Cup holder made for standard sized coffee cups (small, regular, large/grande) as well as normal 330ml and 500ml beverage cans. - - Other sizes (e.g. slim and taller energy drink cans) should fit, too, but I don't have any sample to try.
  • Simply clip the Cup holder into the panel of the door pocket. The bracket is designed to match the inner shape of it perfectly.
  • Move it to a position where it doesn't collide with your seat and legs, I prefer the foremost.
  • Put your cup in there and enjoy! I also use it for my chewing gums.
    It fits to the driver and to the passenger door.

Some questions to be answered in advance to save your time for asking:
Q1: Does it hold big bottles in place?
A1: No, it's a cup holder.
Q2: Why didn't you design it to perfectly fit my cool "red cow" energy drinks?
A2: Cause I don't drink them.
Q3: Don't you hit it with your leg all the time?
A3: No, actually I have quite a clearance in my "natural" sitting position. And also my seat is still pretty far away as you might see in the pictures.
Q4: How reliably does it hold the drinks?
A4: Due to the bracket shape the holder itself is very tight towards the door panel. It won't slip out if you don't want to. The large and medium coffee cups also accurately fit, the cans and the small cup have a little clearance, but they securely stay inside the holder even at strong shaking. So they'll be safe at full braking.
I printed at 0.2mm layers with 95% infill and finished it with the soft part of a hook-and-loop tape for the lower support towards the door panel to avoid vibrations and damage.

My Hario Skerton grinder got wobbly after a bit of use due to the single plastic point of contact for the shaft, so I designed this bearing to hold the shaft in place.

This is a symmetric piece -- you will need to print two. Then take the grinder apart and insert them around the shaft.

I measured the grinder using calipers, then modeled this part in Fusion 360. The F3D file is attached if you would like to modify the source.

Unscrew the grinder and remove the ceramic bits & shaft. Place the two printed parts around the smooth part of the shaft and hold in place. Insert back into the grinder body, aligning the five ribs with those in the grinder body.

comments.text: ...and the reason it's in two pieces instead of one solid piece is...?

comments.text: The threads on the grinder shaft are a wider diameter than the smooth section where this part sits. If the inner diameter of this part was wide enough to fit over the threads it would not be able to serve its intended purpose of holding the shaft steady. Having the part split into two pieces allows it to mate flush against the smooth section of the shaft. Hope this helps!

Modular, user cutomizable, reconfiguarable, flexible footprint,
tool holder "system" (because everything these days has
to be a "System" ;)

Seriously, everyone has their favorite tools and most of us have the
same problem of spending half our time looking for the
tool that we just used or the next tool that we really need
(often the one you just put down and now can't find in the
tool stack that you've been meaning to organize or worse stuck in the "tool-Mug").

This modular tool caddy / tool holder allows you to create
your own custom tool holders for each of your favorite tools and
expand the caddy with new modules beyond the basics that
I designed (in about 10 minutes). Use the "riser" file" to make a second back row that's higher. Use the included "blanks" files to make your own tool holders.

Step 1:

Use the two files called toolHold_End Piece and the file
toolHold_Channel_on_your_machine test to test the design
on your machine. By the way if the files on
your system are initially small when you load them, just
scale up by 10. Measurements will be in metric.
For example the end_piece measures 4x34x33 mm.

Step 2:

Print out a base (standing upright) and a few tool_holders.
Each is labeled for the tool that it was designed to hold
(wow correctly named files, who saw that coming).

Step 3:

Use one of the 1 cm, 2 cm 3cm wide "blanks" to model your own tool holders (or just scale the blank's length to fit your need. By the way if the files on your system are initially small when you load them, just scale up by 10. Measurements will be in metric (sorry I usually model in microns).

Step 4:

  • Get fancy. Design a "two part" tool holder! What I mean is
    design a tool holder that has TWO HALVES, each with a cut
    out for part of the tool (for bigger tools).
  • By the way the groove in the front is for a ruler.
  • Try using just two blanks as spacers without a tool holder.
  • Make a shorter Tool-Holder by scaling the z-axis on the base.
  • Acteone weld the bases into any configuration. For example
    try having a 2x2 or 1x4 (inline) arrangement for multiple holders and use a riser for higher levels. You can even stack the risers.

Have fun!

title: MPCNC Middle Joiner M3 Captive Nut Remix

description.text:
Tightening the screws holding the nut in the Z-nut-lock can be a huge PITA. Often I find it's easier to quickly dissemble than fit a wrench back there.

Worry no-more just print the test print (fast & low infill) first to make sure your printer is calibrated closely to mine (try to put an m3 screw and nut in it, make sure it works) then print two of these with around 60+% infill and ~2.8 layer height After that replace the two screws holding your nut lock with m3 screws and some m3 nuts and tightening them from then on should be much easier.

Careful though a captive nut setup is easy enough to strip so watch the torque.

Haven't used this yet myself as i just reprinted my middle joiners before i made this.

title: Modified and split Z-stage for Ultimaker 2 Aluminum Extrusion 3D printer

description.text:
Been working on the "Ultimaker 2 Aluminum Extrusion 3D printer" on a small printer, so I had to split up the parts to be able to print them.

There are 2 different top and two different bottom pieces. The names should clearly indicate what it is. There are 2 different bottom middel pieces (motor-Mount) where one is shortened a bit in case the 3 pieces making up the bottom gets a bit wide.

Changes:
Top
1.1) Top of Z-stage has been split in two.
1.2) Added a hole for an M3 screw for each top part. REMEMBER you need to add 2 extra T-nuts.
1.3) Enlarged 12mm rod holes to 12,4mm to make them fit after 100% infill (which I strongly recommend)
1.4) Made some build in support in the 12,4mm hole to make it cleaner. Easy to remove afterwards - you CAN use support in addition if you need it for the longish hole in the parts.
1.5) One version of the top pieces has 2mm deeper hole for the 12mm rod (hole is still 12,4mm) and I lengthened the piece in order to move the location of the nut.
1.5) I "accidentially" uploaded a version of the top.right side with build in support. Use it if you like. Same as the other extended model otherwise.

Bottom:
1.1) Split the bottom Z-stage into 3 parts.
1.2) Enlarged 12mm rod holes to 12,4mm to make them fit after 100% infill (which I strongly recommend)
1.3) Filled up the "hole" for the motor in the bottom of the middle section as it made for manual cleaning and enlarging. The motor fits just fine underneath it still. (I use 40mm motor, but larger motors should be fine when you use feets on your case).
1.4) One version of the left and right pieces has 7mm deeper holes for the 12mm rods - holes are still 12.4mm in diamenter.

Do yourself a favor and print with 100% infill. You need these to be rock solid to make for a stable axis, and you really do not save much materiale by doing any less.

I printed with 0.2 layer height, 100% infill and no support. You might want support on the 2 top parts for the horizontal holes if you lack on cooling.
I tested with support in Cura with fine results: Support everywhere - grid - distance X/Y 0.7 - Distance Z 0.6

Use some locking rings if you do not glue the screws and nuts together. If you do not use locking rings I'd recommend using some washers to distribute the pressure from the screws onto the parts.

title: Modified and reinforced Motor mounts for Ultimaker 2 Aluminum Extrusion 3D printer

description.text:
Been working on the "Ultimaker 2 Aluminum Extrusion 3D printer" and had some issues with the motormounts:

The original maker did an outstanding job, but I bumped into some didifficulties and made some changes.

Issues/Changes
Y axis Mount (motor that drives the X axis)
1) Belt was rubbing against part of the motor-Mount, so removed a piece.
2) I enlarged the areas around the screws to make room for washers to spread the stress caused by the screws on the Mount.

Issues/Changes
X axis Mount (motor that drives the Y axis)
1) The 2 screws holding the motor in place, located close to the aluminium extrusions bit into the extrusions.
2) I moved the entire assembly 2mm farther out to mitigate the above - this makes room for the use of washers as well.
3) - After the above change, the belt bit into one section of the motor-Mount, so I removed a small piece/corner.

Print with 100% infill to make it solid. I used 0.2 layers, but I guess any would do.
You might need to drill out the holes for your screws to fit in.

Use support on the X axis Mount (motor that drives the Y axis). Use 3-4 times z-distance as your layerheight - I use 0.7 distance with 0.2 layer-height.

comments.text: Another good fix!  The X-axis is a close fit as far as the 2 screws rubbing on the extrusion. I didn't have that amount of biting into the extrusion. Moving it makes total sense. I was hell bent on keeping all the parts in their exact location as the official UM2. I don't think shifting the motor 2mm will make any difference. I'm actually going to replace my Y-axis mount with yours!  It was another issue I wanted to address... so thanks!

comments.text: You have made an awesome build, which is the reason I bother with the time for small changes :)

A replacement crank arm magnet for the garmin GSC10 cadence sensor. It should work with any other magnetic cadence sensor.

The default magnet is a 1/4"x1/8" (diameter x height) rare earth magnet. You can customize the design for any size but you'll have to convert to mm.

See instructions for assembly and customization notes.

The magnet should interference fit into the part, so make sure you don't choose a magnet diameter that's much too big (diameter+0.2mm worked well for me). I recommend ABS as it's softer but PLA should work if you increase the magnet diameter a little (~0.3-0.4 vs ~0.2) to account for PLA's hardness/brittleness. You can also glue the magnet.

These are the magnets I used (not affiliated w/ them).
http://www.magnet4less.com/product_info.php?cPath=1_11&products_id=100

Assembly:

  1. Print part, no support, raft optional.
  2. Press fit (using a vice makes it really easy) the magnet into the circular magnet shaped hole.
  3. Using the square through hole, mount with a zip tie.

Optionally, you may plastidip after step 2.

description.text:
Attention! This is an experimental model.
More details https://grabcad.com/library/black-clipper-1
Project aims to provide high rigidity and light weight of the quadrocopters frame using 3D printing technology from ABS plastic
The main ideas and ways of their implementation

  1. Design similar to the wildlife more visually attractive and often optimal in terms of strength. For body, motor beams and supports, I used sequentially following programs: Autodesk Inventor (initial surface)-> Rhino->Grasshopper(Cytoskeleton and other plug-ins)->T splines for Rhino (convert mesh to t-splines mesh then T splines mesh to surface) -> Autodesk Inventor (final part). Multi-stage design process takes a long time (counting t-splines took time up to 12 hours). Due to lack of time I was limited in variants of design. In my opinion turned out that somewhere between bionics and steampunk :-)
  2. ABS does not have sufficient rigidity to effectively resist bending load. Items printed on the 3D printer even worse because of the layered structure. We need to build a structure like the sailing ships: tensile load should take strong rope rigging. For quadrocopters role rigging can perform braid fishing line (see more http://www.spiderwire.com ). For example fishing line 0.4 mm, tensile strength up to 30 kg. This braid fishing line is very flexible in contrast to monofilament line. This quadrocopters strength provided by the rigging of the fishing line plastic only provides a form.

author: JackHammer

title: Leapfrog Creatr HS - custom standalone LED light system

description.text:
Hi makers, leapfrog owners and illumination enthusiasts,

here is my own standalone light system for my Leapfrog Creatr HS 3D printer. I create it because the single stripe of blue LED on the back side of the print bed is to less for any print surveillance.

It is powered by 4x 1,5 V (AA) batteries connected to a step-up DC/DC converter that delivers the 12V/DC power for the white 12V LED stripes.

The strips themselve were inside of a standard cable duct (1.1cm width).

For more details see the -> Instructions tab <- or feel free to contact me.

Assembly instructions:

  1. Print the STL files (two small holders are recommended for each side).

  2. You do not have to cut the LED stripe into parts. Look for a blank copper connection for soldering your wire.
    Now, you can just scratch a hole (with a knife - handle with care :) ) into the silicone from the front until you reach the stripe itself.
    Clean the copper with the hot end of your soldering iron.

  3. Clean your soldering iron from the burned silicone and solder the wires on the copper connectors.

  4. Fill the hole with some hot glue and apply a shrink tube to cover it.

  5. Drill a hole into the cable duct where the hole of the backplane holder is located.

  6. Screw down the battery holder, DC/DC converter and the switch on the 3D printed backplane using some short screws (max. 8mm height, flat head).
    Connect the switch between the battery clip and the converter.

  7. Wire up the parts on the backplane. Diagram follows...

  8. Guide the backplane cable duct into its holder and feed in the cable with the LED stripe

  9. Snap in cable duct holder on each side and feed them with the LED stripes.

  10. Switch it on and enjoy the light!

Shopping list:

  • White LED stripe (~2m)
  • Cable duct (~2m) - dimension (inner-width: 1,1cm) - depends on your LED stripe width
  • 4x AA 1,5V batteries

title: Easy to print differential (no support material)

description.text: Working Model of an open differential with a stand to hold it together. Easy to print - requires no or minimal support material (I didn't use any)

Requires about 35 3x8mm flat-head screws. Up to 3x12mm should work as long as they are flat-head or "countersunk". I prefer hex drive like these:
http://www.mcmaster.com/#92125a128/=ynqmb3
Or check eBay

The leading number in each filename indicates how many of that file to print.
The spacer goes around "axle_holder_right". Print a second if there is still too much play.

I made the through-holes 3.6mm and the threading holes 3.1mm because the printer/slicer I'm using under-sizes the holes.
I recommend a test print of "pinion_spindle" first and attempt to thread the 3mm screw to make sure it works. If the holes are too loose, you can try 6-32 x 3/8" flat head like this, they are slightly larger:
http://www.mcmaster.com/#92210a146/=ynrikz

license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Update Sept.2015: Printed several spools (kilograms) with this configuration and it works absolutely great - only feeding a new spool can be a bit tricky as already mentioned below

Printable without support - I included "printhelpers" for the first layer to stick better on the bed which you have to remove (the magenta surfaces on the CAD screenshot)

You will need at least one M5 pneumatic fitting for each side - if you also want to guide the filament into the extruder block you'll need another one each.
I used a piece of an M3 rod and two nuts on the bottom so the rod won't turn when you tighten whatever you have over your spring (i bought M3 kurled nuts)

Sometimes it's a bit tricky to stick the filament into the extruder block caused by the pneumatic fittings - it works everytime at my ZIM but sometimes I need a minute or two ;-)
